# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: coordination-chemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] The word *chelation* is derived from Greek χηλή, *chēlē*, meaning "claw", because the ligand molecule or molecules hold the metal atom like the claws of a crab.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] The term *chelate* (/ˈkiːleɪt/) was first applied in 1920 by Sir Gilbert T.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Chelation is useful in the preparation of nutritional supplements, in chelation therapy to remove toxic metals from the body, as contrast agents in MRI scanning, in manufacturing using homogeneous catalysts, in chemical water treatment to assist in the removal of metals, and in fertilizers.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Bidentate ligands bind to metal ions forming a **chelate ring**.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Ligands of higher denticity form two or more chelate rings.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Ethylenediamine, 2,2'-bipyridine, and 1,10-phenanthroline form C2N2M chelate rings.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Just like in organic chemistry, 5- and 6-membered chelate rings predominate.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] The chelate effect is the greater affinity of chelating ligands for a metal ion than that of similar nonchelating (monodentate) ligands for the same metal.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] The thermodynamic principles underpinning the chelate effect are illustrated by the contrasting affinities of cadmium(II) for ethylenediamine (en) vs. methylamine.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] In (**1**) the ethylenediamine forms a chelate complex with the cadmium ion.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Chelation results in the formation of a five-membered CdC2N2 ring.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] In (**2**) the bidentate ligand is replaced by two monodentate methylamine ligands of approximately the same donor power, indicating that the Cd–N bonds are approximately the same in the two reactions.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] The thermodynamic approach to describing the chelate effect considers the equilibrium constant for the reaction: the larger the equilibrium constant, the higher the concentration of the complex.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Electrical charges have been omitted for simplicity of notation.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] The square brackets indicate concentration, and the subscripts to the stability constants, *β*, indicate the stoichiometry of the complex.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] When the analytical concentration of methylamine is twice that of ethylenediamine and the concentration of copper is the same in both reactions, the concentration [Cd(en)] is much higher than the concentration [Cd(MeNH2)2] because *β*11 ≫ *β*12.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] where *R* is the gas constant and *T* is the temperature in kelvins. ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠ is the standard enthalpy change of the reaction and ⁠ $\Delta S^{\ominus }$ ⁠ is the standard entropy change.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Since the enthalpy should be approximately the same for the two reactions, the difference between the two stability constants is due to the effects of entropy.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] In equation (**1**) there are two particles on the left and one on the right, whereas in equation (**2**) there are three particles on the left and one on the right.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] This difference means that less entropy of disorder is lost when the chelate complex is formed with bidentate ligand than when the complex with monodentate ligands is formed.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] This is one of the factors contributing to the entropy difference.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Other factors include solvation changes and ring formation.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Some experimental data to illustrate the effect are shown in the following table.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] These data confirm that the enthalpy changes are approximately equal for the two reactions and that the main reason for the greater stability of the chelate complex is the entropy term, which is much less unfavorable.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] In general it is difficult to account precisely for thermodynamic values in terms of changes in solution at the molecular level, but it is clear that the chelate effect is predominantly an effect of entropy.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Other explanations, including that of Schwarzenbach, are discussed in Greenwood and Earnshaw (*loc.cit*).
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Numerous biomolecules exhibit the ability to dissolve certain metal cations.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Thus, proteins, polysaccharides, and polynucleic acids are excellent polydentate ligands for many metal ions.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Organic compounds such as the amino acids glutamic acid and histidine, organic diacids such as malate, and polypeptides such as phytochelatin are also typical chelators.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] In addition to these adventitious chelators, several biomolecules are specifically produced to bind certain metals (see next section).
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Virtually all metalloenzymes feature metals that are chelated, usually to peptides or cofactors and prosthetic groups.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Such chelating agents include the porphyrin rings in hemoglobin and chlorophyll.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Many microbial species produce water-soluble pigments that serve as chelating agents, termed siderophores.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] For example, species of *Pseudomonas* are known to secrete pyochelin and pyoverdine that bind iron.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Enterobactin, produced by *E. coli*, is the strongest chelating agent known.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] The marine mussels use metal chelation, especially Fe3+ chelation with the Dopa residues in mussel foot protein-1 to improve the strength of the threads that they use to secure themselves to surfaces.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] In earth science, chemical weathering is attributed to organic chelating agents (e.g., peptides and sugars) that extract metal ions from minerals and rocks.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Most metal complexes in the environment and in nature are bound in some form of chelate ring (e.g., with a humic acid or a protein).
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Thus, metal chelates are relevant to the mobilization of metals in the soil, the uptake and the accumulation of metals into plants and microorganisms.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Selective chelation of heavy metals is relevant to bioremediation (e.g., removal of 137Cs from radioactive waste).
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Synthetic chelates such as ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid (EDTA) proved too stable and not nutritionally viable.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] If the mineral was taken from the EDTA ligand, the ligand could not be used by the body and would be expelled.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] During the expulsion process, the EDTA ligand randomly chelated and stripped other minerals from the body.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] The average weight of the hydrolyzed amino acids must be approximately 150 and the resulting molecular weight of the chelate must not exceed 800 Da.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Since the early development of these compounds, much more research has been conducted, and has been applied to human nutrition products in a similar manner to the animal nutrition experiments that pioneered the technology.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Ferrous bis-glycinate is an example of one of these compounds that has been developed for human nutrition.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Dentin adhesives were first designed and produced in the 1950s based on a co-monomer chelate with calcium on the surface of the tooth and generated very weak water-resistant chemical bonding (2–3 MPa).
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Chelation therapy is an antidote for poisoning by mercury, arsenic, and lead.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Chelating agents convert these metal ions into a chemically and biochemically inert form that can be excreted.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Chelation using sodium calcium edetate has been approved by the U.S.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Food and Drug Administration (FDA) for serious cases of lead poisoning.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] It is not approved for treating "heavy metal toxicity".
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Although beneficial in cases of serious lead poisoning, use of disodium EDTA (edetate disodium) instead of calcium disodium EDTA has resulted in fatalities due to hypocalcemia.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Disodium EDTA is not approved by the FDA for any use, and all FDA-approved chelation therapy products require a prescription.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Chelate complexes of gadolinium are often used as contrast agents in MRI scans, although iron particle and manganese chelate complexes have also been explored.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Bifunctional chelate complexes of zirconium, gallium, fluorine, copper, yttrium, bromine, or iodine are often used for conjugation to monoclonal antibodies for use in antibody-based PET imaging.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] These chelate complexes often employ the usage of hexadentate ligands such as desferrioxamine B (DFO), according to Meijs *et al.*, and the gadolinium complexes often employ the usage of octadentate ligands such as DTPA, according to Desreux *et al*.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Auranofin, a chelate complex of gold, is used in the treatment of rheumatoid arthritis, and penicillamine, which forms chelate complexes of copper, is used in the treatment of Wilson's disease and cystinuria, as well as refractory rheumatoid arthritis.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Chelation in the intestinal tract is a cause of numerous interactions between drugs and metal ions (also known as "minerals" in nutrition).
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] As examples, antibiotic drugs of the tetracycline and quinolone families are chelators of Fe2+, Ca2+, and Mg2+ ions.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] EDTA, which binds to calcium, is used to alleviate the hypercalcemia that often results from band keratopathy.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] The calcium may then be removed from the cornea, allowing for some increase in clarity of vision for the patient.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Homogeneous catalysts are often chelated complexes.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] A representative example is the use of BINAP (a bidentate phosphine) in Noyori asymmetric hydrogenation and asymmetric isomerization.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] The latter has the practical use of manufacture of synthetic (–)-menthol.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] A chelating agent is the main component of some rust removal formulations.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Citric acid is used to soften water in soaps and laundry detergents.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Phosphonates are also well-known chelating agents.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Chelators are used in water treatment programs and specifically in steam engineering.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Although the treatment is often referred to as "softening", chelation has little effect on the water's mineral content, other than to make it soluble and lower the water's pH level.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Metal chelate compounds are common components of fertilizers to provide micronutrients.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] These micronutrients (manganese, iron, zinc, copper) are required for the health of the plants.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Most fertilizers contain phosphate salts that, in the absence of chelating agents, typically convert these metal ions into insoluble solids that are of no nutritional value to the plants.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] EDTA is the typical chelating agent that keeps these metal ions in a soluble form.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Because of their wide needs, the overall chelating agents growth was 4% annually during 2009–2014 and the trend is likely to increase.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Aminopolycarboxylic acids chelators are the most widely consumed chelating agents; however, the percentage of the greener alternative chelators in this category continues to grow.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] The consumption of traditional aminopolycarboxylates chelators, in particular the EDTA (ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid) and NTA (nitrilotriacetic acid), is declining (−6% annually), because of the persisting concerns over their toxicity and negative environmental impact.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] In 2013, these greener alternative chelants represented approximately 15% of the total aminopolycarboxylic acids demand.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] This is expected to rise to around 21% by 2018, replacing and aminophosphonic acids used in cleaning applications.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Examples of some Greener alternative chelating agents include ethylenediamine disuccinic acid (EDDS), polyaspartic acid (PASA), methylglycinediacetic acid (MGDA), glutamic diacetic acid (L-GLDA), citrate, gluconic acid, amino acids, plant extracts etc.
[src:coordination-chemistry/chelation] Dechelation (or de-chelation) is a reverse process of the chelation in which the chelating agent is recovered by acidifying solution with a mineral acid to form a precipitate.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] A **coordination complex** is a chemical compound consisting of a central atom or ion, which is usually metallic and is called the *coordination centre*, and a surrounding array of bound molecules or ions, that are in turn known as *ligands* or complexing agents.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Many metal-containing compounds, especially those that include transition metals (elements like titanium that belong to the periodic table's d-block), are coordination complexes.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The central atom or ion is bonded to a fixed number of donor atoms, a value known as the coordination number; the most common coordination numbers are 2, 4, and 6.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The geometry of the complex such as octahedral, tetrahedral, or square planar depends on the coordination number, the size and charge of the metal ion, and the nature of the ligands.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Many coordination complexes exhibit isomerism, including cis–trans isomerism and optical isomerism.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The systematic study of coordination compounds began in the late 19th century with the work of Christian Wilhelm Blomstrand and Sophus Mads Jørgensen, and was definitively established by Alfred Werner, whose 1893 theory of coordination geometry earned him the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1913.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The electronic structure of coordination complexes, described by crystal field theory and ligand field theory, governs their characteristic properties, including their often vivid colors, their magnetic behavior, and their reactivity.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The colors of transition metal complexes arise from electronic transitions between d orbitals or from charge-transfer processes.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Coordination compounds are found throughout nature and industry.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] In bioinorganic chemistry, metal complexes play essential structural and catalytic roles; examples include the heme group in hemoglobin, chlorophyll, and vitamin B₁₂.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Industrially, coordination compounds are central to homogeneous catalysis, hydrometallurgy, and the synthesis of pigments and polymers.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The stability of a complex in solution is quantified by its stability constant.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Coordination complexes are so pervasive that their structures and reactions are described in many ways, sometimes confusingly.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The atom within a ligand that is bonded to the central metal atom or ion is called the **donor atom**.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] In a typical complex, a metal ion is bonded to several donor atoms, which can be the same or different.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] A polydentate (multiple bonded) ligand is a molecule or ion that bonds to the central atom through several of the ligand's atoms; ligands with 2, 3, 4 or even 6 bonds to the central atom are common.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] These complexes are called chelate complexes; the formation of such complexes is called chelation, complexation, and coordination.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The central atom or ion, together with all ligands, comprise the coordination sphere.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The central atoms or ion and the donor atoms comprise the first coordination sphere.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The number of donor atoms attached to the central atom or ion is called the coordination number.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The most common coordination numbers are 2, 4, and especially 6.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] A hydrated ion is one kind of a complex ion (or simply a complex), a species formed between a central metal ion and one or more surrounding ligands, molecules or ions that contain at least one lone pair of electrons.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] If all the ligands are monodentate, then the number of donor atoms equals the number of ligands.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] For example, the cobalt(II) hexahydrate ion or the hexaaquacobalt(II) ion [Co(H2O)6]2+ is a hydrated-complex ion that consists of six water molecules attached to a metal ion Co.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The oxidation state and the coordination number reflect the number of bonds formed between the metal ion and the ligands in the complex ion.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] However, the coordination number of Pt(en)2+ 2 is 4 (rather than 2) since it has two bidentate ligands, which contain four donor atoms in total.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Any donor atom will give a pair of electrons.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] There are some donor atoms or groups which can offer more than one pair of electrons.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Such are called bidentate (offers two pairs of electrons) or polydentate (offers more than two pairs of electrons).
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] In some cases an atom or a group offers a pair of electrons to two similar or different central metal atoms or acceptors—by division of the electron pair—into a three-center two-electron bond.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Coordination complexes have been known since the beginning of modern chemistry.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Early well-known coordination complexes include dyes such as Prussian blue.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Their properties were first well understood in the late 1800s, following the 1869 work of Christian Wilhelm Blomstrand.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Blomstrand developed what has come to be known as the *complex ion chain theory.* In considering metal amine complexes, he theorized that the ammonia molecules compensated for the charge of the ion by forming chains of the type [(NH3)X]X+, where X is the coordination number of the metal ion.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] He compared his theoretical ammonia chains to hydrocarbons of the form (CH2)X.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Following this theory, Danish scientist Sophus Mads Jørgensen made improvements to it.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] In his version of the theory, Jørgensen claimed that when a molecule dissociates in a solution there were two possible outcomes: the ions would bind via the ammonia chains Blomstrand had described or the ions would bind directly to the metal.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] It was not until 1893 that the most widely accepted version of the theory today was published by Alfred Werner.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Werner's work included two important changes to the Blomstrand theory.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The first was that Werner described the two possibilities in terms of location in the coordination sphere.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] He claimed that if the ions were to form a chain, this would occur outside of the coordination sphere while the ions that bound directly to the metal would do so within the coordination sphere.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Werner also disproved the majority of the chain theory.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Werner discovered the spatial arrangements of the ligands that were involved in the formation of the complex hexacoordinate cobalt.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] His theory explained the difference between a coordinated ligand and a charge-balancing ion in a compound for example, the chloride ion in the cobaltammine chlorides and accounted for many previously inexplicable isomers.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] In 1911, Werner first resolved the cobalt/ammonia coordination complex hexol into optical isomers, overthrowing the theory that only carbon compounds could possess chirality.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The ions or molecules surrounding the central atom are called ligands.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Ligands are classified as L or X (or a combination thereof), depending on how many electrons they provide for the bond between ligand and central atom.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] L ligands provide two electrons from a lone electron pair, resulting in a coordinate covalent bond.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] X ligands provide one electron, with the central atom providing the other electron, thus forming a regular covalent bond.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The ligands are said to be **coordinated** to the atom.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] For alkenes, the pi bonds can coordinate to metal atoms.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] An example is ethylene in the complex [PtCl3(C2H4)]− (Zeise's salt).
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] In coordination chemistry, a structure is first described by its coordination number, the number of ligands attached to the metal (more specifically, the number of donor atoms).
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Usually one can count the ligands attached, but sometimes even the counting can become ambiguous.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Coordination numbers are normally between two and nine, but large numbers of ligands are not uncommon for the lanthanides and actinides.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The number of bonds depends on the size, charge, and electron configuration of the metal ion and the ligands.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Metal ions may have more than one coordination number.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Typically the chemistry of transition metal complexes is dominated by interactions between s and p molecular orbitals of the donor-atoms in the ligands and the d orbitals of the metal ions.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The s, p, and d orbitals of the metal can accommodate 18 electrons (see 18-Electron rule).
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The maximum coordination number for a certain metal is thus related to the electronic configuration of the metal ion (to be more specific, the number of empty orbitals) and to the ratio of the size of the ligands and the metal ion.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Large metals and small ligands lead to high coordination numbers, e.g. [Mo(CN)8]4−.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Small metals with large ligands lead to low coordination numbers, e.g.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Due to their large size, lanthanides, actinides, and early transition metals tend to have high coordination numbers.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The idealized descriptions of 5-, 7-, 8-, and 9- coordination are often indistinct geometrically from alternative structures with slightly differing L-M-L (ligand-metal-ligand) angles, e.g. the difference between square pyramidal and trigonal bipyramidal structures.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] To distinguish between the alternative coordinations for five-coordinated complexes, the τ geometry index was invented by Addison et al.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] This index depends on angles by the coordination center and changes between 0 for the square pyramidal to 1 for trigonal bipyramidal structures, allowing to classify the cases in between.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] This system was later extended to four-coordinated complexes by Houser et al. and also Okuniewski et al.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Many kinds of isomerism exist in coordination complexes.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Just as in organic chemistry, isomers are of two types: diastereomers (also called diastereoisomers) and enantiomers.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Enantiomers are non-superimposable mirror images.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Diastereomers are all other types of isomers.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Cis–trans isomerism occurs in octahedral and square planar complexes (but not tetrahedral).
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] When two ligands are adjacent they are said to be **cis**, when opposite each other, **trans**.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] When three identical ligands occupy one face of an octahedron, the isomer is said to be facial, or **fac**.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] In a *fac* isomer, any two identical ligands are adjacent or *cis* to each other.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] If these three ligands and the metal ion are in one plane, the isomer is said to be meridional, or **mer**.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] A *mer* isomer can be considered as a combination of a *trans* and a *cis*, since it contains both trans and cis pairs of identical ligands.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Optical isomerism occurs when a complex is not superimposable with its mirror image.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] It is so called because the two isomers are each optically active, that is, they rotate the plane of polarized light in opposite directions.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] In the first molecule shown, the symbol Λ (*lambda*) is used as a prefix to describe the left-handed propeller twist formed by three bidentate ligands.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The second molecule is the mirror image of the first, with the symbol Δ (*delta*) as a prefix for the right-handed propeller twist.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The third and fourth molecules are a similar pair of Λ and Δ isomers, in this case with two bidentate ligands and two identical monodentate ligands.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Structural isomerism occurs when the bonds are themselves different.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Four types of structural isomerism are recognized: ionisation isomerism, solvate or hydrate isomerism, linkage isomerism and coordination isomerism.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Solvate or hydrate isomerism – the isomers have the same composition but differ with respect to the number of molecules of solvent that serve as ligand vs simply occupying sites in the crystal.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Examples: [Cr(H2O)6]Cl3 is violet colored, [CrCl(H2O)5]Cl2·H2O is blue-green, and [CrCl2(H2O)4]Cl·2H2O is dark green.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] **Linkage isomerism** occurs with ligands with more than one possible donor atom, known as ambidentate ligands.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] For example, nitrite can coordinate through O or N.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] One pair of nitrite linkage isomers have structures (NH3)5CoNO2+2 (nitro isomer) and (NH3)5CoONO2+ (nitrito isomer).
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] **Coordination isomerism** occurs when both positive and negative ions of a salt are complex ions and the two isomers differ in the distribution of ligands between the cation and the anion.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Many of the properties of transition metal complexes are dictated by their electronic structures.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The electronic structure can be described by a relatively ionic model that ascribes formal charges to the metals and ligands.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] This approach is the essence of crystal field theory (CFT).
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Crystal field theory, introduced by Hans Bethe in 1929, gives a quantum mechanically based attempt at understanding complexes.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] But crystal field theory treats all interactions in a complex as ionic and assumes that the ligands can be approximated by negative point charges.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] More sophisticated models embrace covalency, and this approach is described by ligand field theory (LFT) and molecular orbital theory (MO).
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Ligand field theory, introduced in 1935 and built from molecular orbital theory, can handle a broader range of complexes and can explain complexes in which the interactions are covalent.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The chemical applications of group theory can aid in the understanding of crystal or ligand field theory, by allowing simple, symmetry based solutions to the formal equations.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Chemists tend to employ the simplest model required to predict the properties of interest; for this reason, CFT has been a favorite for the discussions when possible.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] MO and LF theories are more complicated, but provide a more realistic perspective.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Transition metal complexes often have spectacular colors caused by electronic transitions by the absorption of light.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] For this reason they are often applied as pigments.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Most transitions that are related to colored metal complexes are either d–d transitions or charge transfer bands.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] In a d–d transition, an electron in a d orbital on the metal is excited by a photon to another d orbital of higher energy, therefore d–d transitions occur only for partially-filled d-orbital complexes (d1–9).
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] For complexes having d0 or d10 configuration, charge transfer is still possible even though d–d transitions are not.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] A charge transfer band entails promotion of an electron from a metal-based orbital into an empty ligand-based orbital (metal-to-ligand charge transfer or MLCT).
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The converse also occurs: excitation of an electron in a ligand-based orbital into an empty metal-based orbital (ligand-to-metal charge transfer or LMCT).
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] These phenomena can be observed with the aid of electronic spectroscopy; also known as UV-Vis.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] For simple compounds with high symmetry, the d–d transitions can be assigned using Tanabe–Sugano diagrams.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] These assignments are gaining increased support with computational chemistry.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Superficially lanthanide complexes are similar to those of the transition metals in that some are colored.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] However, for the common Ln3+ ions (Ln = lanthanide) the colors are all pale, and hardly influenced by the nature of the ligand.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The colors are due to 4f electron transitions.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] As the 4f orbitals in lanthanides are "buried" in the xenon core and shielded from the ligand by the 5s and 5p orbitals they are therefore not influenced by the ligands to any great extent leading to a much smaller crystal field splitting than in the transition metals.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The absorption spectra of an Ln3+ ion approximates to that of the free ion where the electronic states are described by spin-orbit coupling.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] This contrasts to the transition metals where the ground state is split by the crystal field.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] This can lead to extremely unusual effects, such as significant color changes under different forms of lighting.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Metal complexes that have unpaired electrons are paramagnetic.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] This can be due to an odd number of electrons overall, or to incomplete electron-pairing.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Thus, monomeric Ti(III) species have one "d-electron" and must be (para)magnetic, regardless of the geometry or the nature of the ligands.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Ti(II), with two d-electrons, forms some complexes that have two unpaired electrons and others with none.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] This effect is illustrated by the compounds TiX2[(CH3)2PCH2CH2P(CH3)2]2: when X = Cl, the complex is paramagnetic (high-spin configuration), whereas when X = CH3, it is diamagnetic (low-spin configuration).
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Ligands provide an important means of adjusting the ground state properties.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] In bi- and polymetallic complexes, in which the individual centres have an odd number of electrons or that are high-spin, the situation is more complicated.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] If there is interaction (either direct or through ligand) between the two (or more) metal centres, the electrons may couple (antiferromagnetic coupling, resulting in a diamagnetic compound), or they may enhance each other (ferromagnetic coupling).
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] When there is no interaction, the two (or more) individual metal centers behave as if in two separate molecules.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] If the ligands around the metal are carefully chosen, the metal can aid in (stoichiometric or catalytic) transformations of molecules or be used as a sensor.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Metal complexes, also known as coordination compounds, include virtually all metal compounds.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The study of "coordination chemistry" is the study of "inorganic chemistry" of all alkali and alkaline earth metals, transition metals, lanthanides, actinides, and metalloids.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Thus, coordination chemistry is the chemistry of the majority of the periodic table.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Metals and metal ions exist, in the condensed phases at least, only surrounded by ligands.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Many natural ligands are "classical" especially including water.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] , in which a cluster is embedded in a biologically active species.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Mineralogy, materials science, and solid state chemistry – as they apply to metal ions – are subsets of coordination chemistry in the sense that the metals are surrounded by ligands.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] In many cases these ligands are oxides or sulfides, but the metals are coordinated nonetheless, and the principles and guidelines discussed below apply.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] In hydrates, at least some of the ligands are water molecules.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] It is true that the focus of mineralogy, materials science, and solid state chemistry differs from the usual focus of coordination or inorganic chemistry.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The former are concerned primarily with polymeric structures, properties arising from a collective effects of many highly interconnected metals.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] In contrast, coordination chemistry focuses on reactivity and properties of complexes containing individual metal atoms or small ensembles of metal atoms.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The ligands' names are given in alphabetical order.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Numerical prefixes do not affect the order.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] If the complex is an anion, the central atom's name will end in *-ate*, and its Latin name will be used if available (except for mercury).
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The oxidation state of the central atom is to be specified (when it is one of several possible, or zero), and should be written as a Roman numeral (or 0) enclosed in parentheses.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Name of the cation should be preceded by the name of anion.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The coordination number of ligands attached to more than one metal (bridging ligands) is indicated by a subscript to the Greek symbol μ placed before the ligand name.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Thus the dimer of aluminium trichloride is described by Al2Cl4(μ2-Cl)2.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Any anionic group can be electronically stabilized by any cation.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] An anionic complex can be stabilised by a hydrogen cation, becoming an acidic complex which can dissociate to release the cationic hydrogen.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] This kind of complex compound has a name with "ic" added after the central metal.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] For example, H2[Pt(CN)4] has the name tetracyanoplatinic (II) acid.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The affinity of metal ions for ligands is described by a stability constant, also called the formation constant, and is represented by the symbol Kf.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] where : x, y, and z are the stoichiometric coefficients of each species.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] M stands for metal / metal ion, the L for Lewis bases, and finally Z for complex ions.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Large values indicate that the metal has high affinity for the ligand, provided the system is at equilibrium.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Sometimes the stability constant will be in a different form known as the constant of destability.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] This constant is expressed as the inverse of the constant of formation and is denoted as Kd = 1/Kf .
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] This constant represents the reverse reaction for the decomposition of a complex ion into its individual metal and ligand components.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] When comparing the values for Kd, the larger the value, the more unstable the complex ion is.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] As a result of these complex ions forming in solutions they also can play a key role in solubility of other compounds.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] When a complex ion is formed it can alter the concentrations of its components in the solution.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] If these reactions both occurred in the same reaction vessel, the solubility of the silver chloride would be increased by the presence of NH4OH because formation of the Diammine argentum(I) complex consumes a significant portion of the free silver ions from the solution.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] By Le Chatelier's principle, this causes the equilibrium reaction for the dissolving of the silver chloride, which has silver ion as a product, to shift to the right.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] This new solubility can be calculated given the values of Kf and Ksp for the original reactions.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] The solubility is found essentially by combining the two separate equilibria into one combined equilibrium reaction and this combined reaction is the one that determines the new solubility.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] As metals only exist in solution as coordination complexes, it follows then that this class of compounds is useful in a wide variety of ways.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] In bioinorganic chemistry and bioorganometallic chemistry, coordination complexes serve either structural or catalytic functions.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] An estimated 30% of proteins contain metal ions.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Examples include the intensely colored vitamin B12, the heme group in hemoglobin, the cytochromes, the chlorin group in chlorophyll, and carboxypeptidase, a hydrolytic enzyme important in digestion.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Another complex ion enzyme is catalase, which decomposes the cell's waste hydrogen peroxide.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Synthetic coordination compounds are also used to bind to proteins and especially nucleic acids (e.g. anticancer drug cisplatin).
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Homogeneous catalysis is a major application of coordination compounds for the production of organic substances.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Processes include hydrogenation, hydroformylation, oxidation.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] In one example, a combination of titanium trichloride and triethylaluminium gives rise to Ziegler–Natta catalysts, used for the polymerization of ethylene and propylene to give polymers of great commercial importance as fibers, films, and plastics.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Nickel, cobalt, and copper can be extracted using hydrometallurgical processes involving complex ions.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] They are extracted from their ores as ammine complexes.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Metals can also be separated using the selective precipitation and solubility of complex ions.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Cyanide is used chiefly for extraction of gold and silver from their ores.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Phthalocyanine complexes are an important class of pigments.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] At one time, coordination compounds were used to identify the presence of metals in a sample.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-complex] Qualitative inorganic analysis has largely been superseded by instrumental methods of analysis such as atomic absorption spectroscopy (AAS), inductively coupled plasma atomic emission spectroscopy (ICP-AES) and inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry (ICP-MS).
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] In chemistry, crystallography, and materials science, the **coordination number**, also called **ligancy**, of a central atom in a molecule or crystal is the number of atoms, molecules or ions bonded to it.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] The ion/molecule/atom surrounding the central ion/molecule/atom is called a ligand.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] This number is determined somewhat differently for molecules than for crystals.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] For molecules and polyatomic ions the coordination number of an atom is determined by simply counting the other atoms to which it is bonded (by either single or multiple bonds).
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] For example, [Cr(NH3)2Cl2Br2]− has Cr3+ as its central cation, which has a coordination number of 6 and is described as *hexacoordinate*.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] In chemistry, **coordination number**, defined originally in 1893 by Alfred Werner, is the total number of neighbors of a central atom in a molecule or ion.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] The concept is most commonly applied to coordination complexes.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] The most common coordination number for *d-*block transition metal complexes is 6.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] The coordination number does not distinguish the geometry of such complexes, i.e. octahedral vs trigonal prismatic.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] For transition metal complexes, coordination numbers range from 2 (e.g., AuI in Ph3PAuCl) to 9 (e.g., ReVII in [ReH9]2−).
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] Metals in the *f*-block (the lanthanoids and actinoids) can accommodate higher coordination number due to their greater ionic radii and availability of more orbitals for bonding.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] Coordination numbers of 8 to 12 are commonly observed for *f*-block elements.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] For example, with bidentate nitrate ions as ligands, CeIV and ThIV form the 12-coordinate ions [Ce(NO3)6]2− (ceric ammonium nitrate) and [Th(NO3)6]2−.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] When the surrounding ligands are much smaller than the central atom, even higher coordination numbers may be possible.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] One computational chemistry study predicted a particularly stable PbHe2+ 15 ion composed of a central lead ion coordinated with no fewer than 15 helium atoms.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] Among the Frank–Kasper phases, the packing of metallic atoms can give coordination numbers of up to 16.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] At the opposite extreme, steric shielding can give rise to unusually low coordination numbers.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] An extremely rare instance of a metal adopting a coordination number of 1 occurs in the terphenyl-based arylthallium(I) complex 2,6-Tipp2C6H3Tl, where Tipp is the 2,4,6-triisopropylphenyl group.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] Coordination numbers become ambiguous when dealing with polyhapto ligands.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] For π-electron ligands such as the cyclopentadienide ion [C5H5]−, alkenes and the cyclooctatetraenide ion [C8H8]2−, the number of adjacent atoms in the π-electron system that bind to the central atom is termed the hapticity.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] In ferrocene the hapticity, *η*, of each cyclopentadienide anion is five, Fe(*η*5-C5H5)2.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] Various ways exist for assigning the contribution made to the coordination number of the central iron atom by each cyclopentadienide ligand.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] The contribution could be assigned as one since there is one ligand, or as five since there are five neighbouring atoms, or as three since there are three electron pairs involved.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] Normally the count of electron pairs is taken.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] The coordination numbers are well defined for atoms in the interior of a crystal lattice: one counts the nearest neighbors in all directions.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] The number of neighbors of an interior atom is termed the **bulk coordination number**.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] For surfaces, the number of neighbors is more limited, so the **surface coordination number** is smaller than the bulk coordination number.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] Often the surface coordination number is unknown or variable.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] The surface coordination number is also dependent on the Miller indices of the surface.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] In a body-centered cubic (BCC) crystal, the bulk coordination number is 8, whereas, for the (100) surface, the surface coordination number is 4.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] A common way to determine the coordination number of an atom is by X-ray crystallography.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] Related techniques include neutron or electron diffraction.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] The coordination number of an atom can be determined straightforwardly by counting nearest neighbors.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] The two most common allotropes of carbon have different coordination numbers.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] In diamond, each carbon atom is at the centre of a regular tetrahedron formed by four other carbon atoms, the coordination number is four, as for methane.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] Graphite is made of two-dimensional layers in which each carbon is covalently bonded to three other carbons; atoms in other layers are further away and are not nearest neighbours, giving a coordination number of 3.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] For chemical compounds with regular lattices such as sodium chloride and caesium chloride, a count of the nearest neighbors gives a good picture of the environment of the ions.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] In sodium chloride each sodium ion has 6 chloride ions as nearest neighbours (at 276 pm) at the corners of an octahedron and each chloride ion has 6 sodium atoms (also at 276 pm) at the corners of an octahedron.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] In caesium chloride each caesium has 8 chloride ions (at 356 pm) situated at the corners of a cube and each chloride has eight caesium ions (also at 356 pm) at the corners of a cube.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] International Union of Crystallography, IUCR, states that the coordination number of an atom in a crystalline solid depends on the chemical bonding model and the way in which the coordination number is calculated.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] In some compounds the metal-ligand bonds may not all be at the same distance.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] For example in PbCl2, the coordination number of Pb2+ depends on which chlorides are assigned as ligands.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] Seven chloride ligands have Pb-Cl distances of 280–309 pm.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] Two chloride ligands are more distant, with a Pb-Cl distances of 370 pm.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] For example, zinc has a distorted hexagonal close packed structure.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] Regular hexagonal close packing of spheres would predict that each atom has 12 nearest neighbours and a triangular orthobicupola (also called an anticuboctahedron or twinned cuboctahedron) coordination polyhedron.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] In zinc there are only 6 nearest neighbours at 266 pm in the same close packed plane with six other, next-nearest neighbours, equidistant, three in each of the close packed planes above and below at 291 pm.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] The coordination number of Zn can be assigned as 12 rather than 6.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] Similar considerations can be applied to the regular body centred cube structure where in addition to the 8 nearest neighbors there 6 more, approximately 15% more distant, and in this case the coordination number is often considered to be 14.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] In Nickel arsenide (NiAs) and several related compounds, the coordination number of the metal is ambiguous.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] The metal is bound to six As ligands, but also has two Ni---Ni contacts that could qualify as bonds.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] Two other examples of commonly-encountered chemicals are Fe2O3 and TiO2.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] Fe2O3 has a crystal structure that can be described as having a near close packed array of oxygen atoms with iron atoms filling two thirds of the octahedral holes.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] However each iron atom has 3 nearest neighbors and 3 others a little further away.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] The structure is quite complex, the oxygen atoms are coordinated to four iron atoms and the iron atoms in turn share vertices, edges and faces of the distorted octahedra.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] The titanium atoms 6-coordinate, 2 atoms at 198.3 pm and 4 at 194.6 pm, in a slightly distorted octahedron.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] The octahedra around the titanium atoms share edges and vertices to form a 3-D network.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] The oxide ions are 3-coordinate in a trigonal planar configuration.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] Frequently a gap can be found in the distribution of the interatomic distance of the neighboring atoms: if the shortest distance to a neighboring atom is set equal to 1, then often further atoms are found at distances between 1 and 1.3, and after them follows a gap in which no atoms are found.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] where $d_{1}$ is the distance to the closest atom, $d_{g}$ is the distance to the first atom beyond the gap and $d_{i}$ is the distance to the *i*-th atom in the region between $d_{1}$ and $d_{g}$ .
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] This method is however of no help when no clear gap can be discerned.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] A mathematically unique method of calculation considers the domain of influence (also called Voronoi polyhedron, Wigner-Seitz cell or Dirichlet domain).
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] The domain is constructed by connecting the atom in question with all surrounding atoms; the set of planes perpendicular to the connecting lines and passing through their midpoints forms the domain of influence, which is a convex polyhedron.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] In this way, a polyhedron face can be assigned to every neighboring atom, the area of the face serving as measure for the weighting.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] A value of 1 is assigned to the largest face.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] where n = 5 or 6, $d_{i}$ is the distance to the *i*-th atom and $d_{1}$ is the shortest distance or the assumed standard distance.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] The coordination number of systems with disorder cannot be precisely defined.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] The **first coordination number** can be defined using the radial distribution function *g*(*r*): $n_{1}=4\pi \int _{r_{0}}^{r_{1}}r^{2}g(r)\rho \,dr,$ where *r*0 is the rightmost position starting from *r* = 0 whereon *g*(*r*) is approximately zero, *r*1 is the first minimum.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] Therefore, it is the area under the first peak of *g*(*r*).
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] Alternative definitions for the coordination number can be found in literature, but in essence the main idea is the same.
[src:coordination-chemistry/coordination-number] The **first coordination shell** is the spherical shell with radius between *r*0 and *r*1 around the central particle under investigation.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] In inorganic chemistry, **crystal field theory** (**CFT**) describes the breaking of degeneracies of electron orbital states, usually *d* or *f* orbitals, due to a static electric field produced by a surrounding charge distribution (anion neighbors).
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] This theory has been used to describe various spectroscopies of transition metal coordination complexes, in particular optical spectra (colors).
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] CFT successfully accounts for some magnetic properties, colors, hydration enthalpies, and spinel structures of transition metal complexes, but it does not attempt to describe bonding.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] CFT was developed by physicists Hans Bethe and John Hasbrouck van Vleck in the 1930s.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] CFT was subsequently combined with molecular orbital theory to form the more realistic and complex ligand field theory (LFT), which delivers insight into the process of chemical bonding in transition metal complexes.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] CFT can be complicated further by breaking assumptions made of relative metal and ligand orbital energies, requiring the use of inverted ligand field theory (ILFT) to better describe bonding.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] According to crystal field theory, the interaction between a transition metal and ligands arises from the attraction between the positively charged metal cation and the negative charge on the non-bonding electrons of the ligand.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] The theory is developed by considering energy changes of the five degenerate *d*-orbitals upon being surrounded by an array of point charges consisting of the ligands.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] As a ligand approaches the metal ion, the electrons from the ligand will be closer to some of the *d*-orbitals and farther away from others, causing a loss of degeneracy.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] The electrons in the *d*-orbitals and those in the ligand repel each other due to repulsion between like charges.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] Thus the d-electrons closer to the ligands will have a higher energy than those further away which results in the *d*-orbitals splitting in energy.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] The most common type of complex is octahedral, in which six ligands form the vertices of an octahedron around the metal ion.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] The three lower-energy orbitals are collectively referred to as **t2g**, and the two higher-energy orbitals as **eg**.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] These labels are based on the theory of molecular symmetry: they are the names of irreducible representations of the octahedral point group, Oh.(see the Oh character table) Typical orbital energy diagrams are given below in the section High-spin and low-spin.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] Tetrahedral complexes are the second most common type; here four ligands form a tetrahedron around the metal ion.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] In a tetrahedral crystal field splitting, the *d*-orbitals again split into two groups, with an energy difference of **Δtet**.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] The lower energy orbitals will be *d**z*2 and *d**x*2-*y*2, and the higher energy orbitals will be *d**xy*, *d**xz* and *d**yz* - opposite to the octahedral case.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] Furthermore, since the ligand electrons in tetrahedral symmetry are not oriented directly towards the *d*-orbitals, the energy splitting will be lower than in the octahedral case.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] Square planar and other complex geometries can also be described by CFT.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] The size of the gap Δ between the two or more sets of orbitals depends on several factors, including the ligands and geometry of the complex.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] Some ligands always produce a small value of Δ, while others always give a large splitting.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] The reasons behind this can be explained by ligand field theory.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] It is useful to note that the ligands producing the most splitting are those that can engage in metal to ligand back-bonding.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] The oxidation state of the metal also contributes to the size of Δ between the high and low energy levels.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] As the oxidation state increases for a given metal, the magnitude of Δ increases.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] A V3+ complex will have a larger Δ than a V2+ complex for a given set of ligands, as the difference in charge density allows the ligands to be closer to a V3+ ion than to a V2+ ion.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] The smaller distance between the ligand and the metal ion results in a larger Δ, because the ligand and metal electrons are closer together and therefore repel more.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] Ligands which cause a large splitting Δ of the *d*-orbitals are referred to as strong-field ligands, such as CN− and CO from the spectrochemical series.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] In complexes with these ligands, it is unfavourable to put electrons into the high energy orbitals.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] Therefore, the lower energy orbitals are completely filled before population of the upper sets starts according to the Aufbau principle.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] Complexes such as this are called "low spin".
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] For example, NO2− is a strong-field ligand and produces a large Δ.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] The octahedral ion [Fe(NO2)6]3−, which has 5 *d*-electrons, would have the octahedral splitting diagram shown at right with all five electrons in the *t*2*g* level.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] This low spin state therefore does not follow Hund's rule.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] Conversely, ligands (like I− and Br−) which cause a small splitting Δ of the *d*-orbitals are referred to as weak-field ligands.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] In this case, it is easier to put electrons into the higher energy set of orbitals than it is to put two into the same low-energy orbital, because two electrons in the same orbital repel each other.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] So, one electron is put into each of the five *d*-orbitals in accord with Hund's rule, and "high spin" complexes are formed before any pairing occurs.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] For example, Br− is a weak-field ligand and produces a small Δoct.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] So, the ion [FeBr6]3−, again with five *d*-electrons, would have an octahedral splitting diagram where all five orbitals are singly occupied.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] In order for low spin splitting to occur, the energy cost of placing an electron into an already singly occupied orbital must be less than the cost of placing the additional electron into an e*g* orbital at an energy cost of Δ.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] As noted above, e*g* refers to the *d**z*2 and *d**x*2-*y*2 which are higher in energy than the t2g in octahedral complexes.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] If the energy required to pair two electrons is greater than Δ, the energy cost of placing an electron in an e*g*, high spin splitting occurs.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] The crystal field splitting energy for tetrahedral metal complexes (four ligands) is referred to as Δtet, and is roughly equal to 4/9Δoct (for the same metal and same ligands).
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] Therefore, the energy required to pair two electrons is typically higher than the energy required for placing electrons in the higher energy orbitals.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] Thus, tetrahedral complexes are usually high-spin.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] The use of these splitting diagrams can aid in the prediction of magnetic properties of co-ordination compounds.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] A compound that has unpaired electrons in its splitting diagram will be paramagnetic and will be attracted by magnetic fields, while a compound that lacks unpaired electrons in its splitting diagram will be diamagnetic and will be weakly repelled by a magnetic field.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] The crystal field stabilization energy (CFSE) is the stability that results from placing a transition metal ion in the crystal field generated by a set of ligands.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] It arises due to the fact that when the *d*-orbitals are split in a ligand field (as described above), some of them become lower in energy than before with respect to a spherical field known as the barycenter in which all five *d*-orbitals are degenerate.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] For example, in an octahedral case, the *t2g* set becomes lower in energy than the orbitals in the barycenter.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] As a result of this, if there are any electrons occupying these orbitals, the metal ion is more stable in the ligand field relative to the barycenter by an amount known as the CFSE.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] Conversely, the *eg* orbitals (in the octahedral case) are higher in energy than in the barycenter, so putting electrons in these reduces the amount of CFSE.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] If the splitting of the *d*-orbitals in an octahedral field is Δoct, the three *t2g* orbitals are stabilized relative to the barycenter by 2/5 Δoct, and the *eg* orbitals are destabilized by 3/5 Δoct.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] As examples, consider the two *d*5 configurations shown further up the page.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] The low-spin (top) example has five electrons in the *t2g* orbitals, so the total CFSE is 5 x 2/5 Δoct = 2Δoct.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] In the high-spin (lower) example, the CFSE is (3 x 2/5 Δoct) - (2 x 3/5 Δoct) = 0 - in this case, the stabilization generated by the electrons in the lower orbitals is canceled out by the destabilizing effect of the electrons in the upper orbitals.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] The optical properties (details of absorption and emission spectra) of many coordination complexes can be explained by Crystal Field Theory.
[src:coordination-chemistry/crystal-field-stabilization-energy] Often, however, the deeper colors of metal complexes arise from more intense charge-transfer excitations.
[src:coordination-chemistry/denticity] In coordination chemistry, **denticity** (from Latin *dentis* 'tooth') refers to the number of donor groups in a given ligand that bind to the central metal atom in a coordination complex.
[src:coordination-chemistry/denticity] In many cases, only one atom in the ligand binds to the metal, so the denticity equals one, and the ligand is said to be **unidentate** or **monodentate**.
[src:coordination-chemistry/denticity] Ligands with more than one bonded atom are called **multidentate** or **polydentate**.
[src:coordination-chemistry/denticity] The denticity of a ligand is described with the Greek letter κ ('kappa').
[src:coordination-chemistry/denticity] For example, κ6-EDTA describes an EDTA ligand that coordinates through 6 non-contiguous atoms.
[src:coordination-chemistry/denticity] Denticity is different from hapticity because hapticity refers exclusively to ligands where the coordinating atoms are contiguous.
[src:coordination-chemistry/denticity] In these cases the η ('eta') notation is used.
[src:coordination-chemistry/denticity] Bridging ligands use the μ ('mu') notation.
[src:coordination-chemistry/denticity] Polydentate ligands are chelating agents and classified by their denticity.
[src:coordination-chemistry/denticity] Some atoms cannot form the maximum possible number of bonds a ligand could make.
[src:coordination-chemistry/denticity] In that case one or more binding sites of the ligand are unused.
[src:coordination-chemistry/denticity] Such sites can be used to form a bond with another chemical species.
[src:coordination-chemistry/denticity] Larger ions, such as the lanthanides, Ca2+, and Ba2+ prefer coordination numbers greater than 6.
[src:coordination-chemistry/denticity] For firmly binding these ions, ligands of denticity greater than six are often used.
[src:coordination-chemistry/denticity] One example is the triaminopentacarboxylate (APCA) derived from pentetic acid (HO2CH2N(CH2N(CH2CO2H)2)2.
[src:coordination-chemistry/denticity] A related ligand is 1,4,7,10-tetraazacyclododecane-1,4,7,10-tetraacetate (DOTA).
[src:coordination-chemistry/denticity] The conjugate base of diethylenetriaminepentaacetic acid (DTPA) has a high affinity for metal cations.
[src:coordination-chemistry/denticity] In general, the stability of a metal complex correlates with the denticity of the ligands, which can be attributed to the chelate effect.
[src:coordination-chemistry/denticity] Polydentate ligands such as hexa- or octadentate ligands tend to bind metal ions more strongly than ligands of lower denticity, primarily due to entropic factors.
[src:coordination-chemistry/denticity] Stability constants are a quantitative measure to assess the thermodynamic stability of coordination complexes.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] Ligand field theory resulted from combining the principles laid out in molecular orbital theory and crystal field theory, which describe the loss of degeneracy of metal d orbitals in transition metal complexes.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] John Stanley Griffith and Leslie Orgel championed ligand field theory as a more accurate description of such complexes, although the theory originated in the 1930s with the work on magnetism by John Hasbrouck Van Vleck.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] In their paper, they proposed that the chief cause of color differences in transition metal complexes in solution is the incomplete d orbital subshells.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] That is, the unoccupied d orbitals of transition metals participate in bonding, which influences the colors they absorb in solution.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] In ligand field theory, the various d orbitals are affected differently when surrounded by a field of neighboring ligands and are raised or lowered in energy based on the strength of their interaction with the ligands.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] In an octahedral complex, the molecular orbitals created by coordination can be seen as resulting from the donation of two electrons by each of six σ-donor ligands to the *d*-orbitals on the metal.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] In octahedral complexes, ligands approach along the *x*-, *y*- and *z*-axes, so their σ-symmetry orbitals form bonding and anti-bonding combinations with the *d**z*2 and *d**x*2−*y*2 orbitals.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] The *d**xy*, *d**xz* and *d**yz* orbitals remain non-bonding orbitals.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] In molecular symmetry terms, the six lone-pair orbitals from the ligands (one from each ligand) form six symmetry-adapted linear combinations (SALCs) of orbitals, also sometimes called ligand group orbitals (LGOs).
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] The irreducible representations that these span are *a1g*, *t1u* and *eg*.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] The metal also has six valence orbitals that span these irreducible representations - the s orbital is labeled *a1g*, a set of three p-orbitals is labeled *t1u*, and the *d**z*2 and *d**x*2−*y*2 orbitals are labeled *eg*.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] The six σ-bonding molecular orbitals result from the combinations of ligand SALCs with metal orbitals of the same symmetry.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] π bonding in octahedral complexes occurs in two ways: via any ligand *p*-orbitals that are not being used in σ bonding, and via any π or π* molecular orbitals present on the ligand.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] In the usual analysis, the *p*-orbitals of the metal are used for σ bonding (and have the wrong symmetry to overlap with the ligand p or π or π* orbitals anyway), so the π interactions take place with the appropriate metal *d*-orbitals, i.e.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] These are the orbitals that are non-bonding when only σ bonding takes place.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] One important π bonding in coordination complexes is metal-to-ligand π bonding, also called π backbonding.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] It occurs when the LUMOs (lowest unoccupied molecular orbitals) of the ligand are anti-bonding π* orbitals.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] These orbitals are close in energy to the *d**xy*, *d**xz* and *d**yz* orbitals, with which they combine to form bonding orbitals (i.e. orbitals of lower energy than the aforementioned set of *d*-orbitals).
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] The corresponding anti-bonding orbitals are higher in energy than the anti-bonding orbitals from σ bonding so, after the new π bonding orbitals are filled with electrons from the metal *d*-orbitals, ΔO has increased and the bond between the ligand and the metal strengthens.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] The ligands end up with electrons in their π* molecular orbital, so the corresponding π bond within the ligand weakens.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] The other form of coordination π bonding is ligand-to-metal bonding.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] This situation arises when the π-symmetry *p* or π orbitals on the ligands are filled.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] They combine with the *d**xy*, *d**xz* and *d**yz* orbitals on the metal and donate electrons to the resulting π-symmetry bonding orbital between them and the metal.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] The metal-ligand bond is somewhat strengthened by this interaction, but the complementary anti-bonding molecular orbital from ligand-to-metal bonding is not higher in energy than the anti-bonding molecular orbital from the σ bonding.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] It is filled with electrons from the metal *d*-orbitals, however, becoming the HOMO (highest occupied molecular orbital) of the complex.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] For that reason, ΔO decreases when ligand-to-metal bonding occurs.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] The greater stabilization that results from metal-to-ligand bonding is caused by the donation of negative charge away from the metal ion, towards the ligands.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] This allows the metal to accept the σ bonds more easily.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] The combination of ligand-to-metal σ-bonding and metal-to-ligand π-bonding is a synergic effect, as each enhances the other.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] As each of the six ligands has two orbitals of π-symmetry, there are twelve in total.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] The symmetry adapted linear combinations of these fall into four triply degenerate irreducible representations, one of which is of *t2g* symmetry.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] Crystal field theory (CFT) describes how the presence of surrounding ligands affects the energy of the d orbitals in a transition metal ion.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] In an isolated metal ion, the five d orbitals are degenerate meaning they are equal in energy.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] However, when ligands approach the metal center, electrostatic interactions between the ligand electron pairs and the metal d orbitals cause degeneracy, which results the splitting of energy levels.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] In an octahedral complex, six ligands approach the metal ion along the x, y, and z axes.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] The d orbitals that point directly along these axes, namely dx2−y2 and dz2 experience greater repulsion from the ligands and became higher in energy.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] In contrast, the three orbitals placed between the axes (dxy, dxz and dyz) experience less repulsion and are lower in energy, forming the **t2g** set.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] The energy difference between these two groups is called the crystal field splitting energy (Δo).
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] The magnitude of Δo depends on several factors, including the identity of the metal ion, its oxidation state, and the nature of the ligands.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] Strong-field ligands (such as CN⁻ or CO) produce a large splitting, while weak-field ligands (such as I⁻ or Br⁻) result in a smaller splitting.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] In **tetrahedral complexes**, four ligands approach the metal ion between the coordinate axes rather than directly along them.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] As a result, the pattern of orbital splitting is reversed compared to the octahedral case.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] The orbitals dxy, dxz and dyz now experience greater interaction with the ligands and are increased in energy forming t2 set, while dx2−y2 and dz2 are lower in energy forming the eg set.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] Tetrahedral complexes lack a center of inversion (inversion center/symmetry).
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] The labels g(gerade) and u (ungerade)refer to the parity of orbitals when inverted through a central point, which is only possible in centrosymmetric systems like octahedral complexes.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] The splitting energy in tetrahedral complexes is denoted as Δt and it is typically smaller than the octahedral splitting.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] Another important concept associated with crystal field splitting is the distinction between high**-**spin and low-spin configurations.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] When the splitting energy (Δ) is small (weak-field ligands), electrons occupy higher-energy orbitals before pairing, resulting in a high-spin configuration with more unpaired electrons.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] Conversely, when (Δ) is large (strong-field ligands), electrons occupy the lower-energy orbitals first, leading to a low-spin configuration with fewer unpaired electrons.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] Crystal field splitting is an important phenomenon identifying the physical properties of coordination compounds.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] It explains their color, as electronic transitions between split d orbitals absorb visible light, and their magnetic properties, which depend on the number of unpaired electrons.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] Thus, crystal field theory provides a useful framework for understanding and predicting the behavior of transition metal complexes in chemistry.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] The six bonding molecular orbitals that are formed are "filled" with the electrons from the ligands, and electrons from the *d*-orbitals of the metal ion occupy the non-bonding and, in some cases, anti-bonding MOs.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] The energy difference between the latter two types of MOs is called ΔO (O stands for octahedral) and is determined by the nature of the π-interaction between the ligand orbitals with the *d*-orbitals on the central atom.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] As described above, π-donor ligands lead to a small ΔO and are called weak- or low-field ligands, whereas π-acceptor ligands lead to a large value of ΔO and are called strong- or high-field ligands.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] Ligands that are neither π-donor nor π-acceptor give a value of ΔO somewhere in-between.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] The size of ΔO determines the electronic structure of the *d*4 - *d*7 ions.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] The former case is called low-spin, while the latter is called high-spin.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] A small ΔO can be overcome by the energetic gain from not pairing the electrons, leading to high-spin.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] When ΔO is large, however, the spin-pairing energy becomes negligible by comparison and a low-spin state arises.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] The spectrochemical series is an empirically derived list of ligands ordered by the size of the splitting Δ that they produce.
[src:coordination-chemistry/ligand-field-theory] It can be seen that the low-field ligands are all π-donors (such as I−), the high field ligands are π-acceptors (such as CN− and CO), and ligands such as H2O and NH3, which are neither, are in the middle.
